SIMPLE: mood
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mood
<hw>Mood</hw> <pr>(m⟦oomac⟧d)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[The same word as
<ets>mode</ets>, perh. influenced by <ets>mood</ets> temper. See
<er>Mode</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Manner; style; mode; logical
form; musical style; manner of action or being. See <er>Mode</er> which
is the preferable form).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>Manner of conceiving and
expressing action or being, as positive, possible, conditional,
hypothetical, obligatory, imperitive, etc., without regard to other
accidents, such as time, person, number, etc.; <as>as, the indicative
<ex>mood</ex>; the imperitive <ex>mood</ex>; the infinitive
<ex>mood</ex>; the subjunctive <ex>mood</ex>. Same as
<er>Mode</er>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mood</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mood
<hw>Mood</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mood</ets>, <ets>mod</ets>,
AS. <ets>m⟦omac⟧d</ets>mind, feeling, heart, courage; akin to OS. &
OFries. <ets>m⟦omac⟧d</ets>, D. <ets>moed</ets>, OHG. <ets>muot</ets>,
G. <ets>muth</ets>, <ets>mut</ets>, courage, Dan. & Sw. <ets>mod</ets>,
Icel. <ets>m⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧r</ets> wrath, Goth. <ets>m⟦omac⟧ds</ets>.]</ety>
<def>Temper of mind; temporary state of the mind in regard to passion or
feeling; humor; <as>as, a melancholy <ex>mood</ex>; a suppliant
<ex>mood</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till at the last aslaked was his <qex>mood</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fortune is merry,⟦br⟧
And in this <qex>mood</qex> will give us anything.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The desperate recklessness of her <qex>mood</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mooder</ent>⟦br⟧
